column168: AFTER THOROUGH INVESTIGATION AND DRIVER QUESTIONING, WE CAME TO THE CONCLUSION THAT THE DOMELID GASKET WAS WORN FROM HEAT EXPOSURE AND PRODUCT RAN INTO THE OVERFLOW TUBES AND HARDENED. DUE TO THE EXTREME TEMPERATURES IN THE AREA, THE PRODUCT THAT COLLECTED IN THE OVERLFLOW TUBES BEGAN TO SOFTEN AND STARTED TO RUN FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER TO THE BOTTOM DISCHARGE. AT THAT TIME OF THE SPILL, CLEANUP CREWS WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. IN CONCLUSION, ALL ASPHALT TANKERS OPERATED BY SEABOARD TANK LINES, INC. WILL BE INSPECTED AND WORN GASKETS WILL BE REPLACED ALONG WITH ANY OTHER ITEMS THAT APPEAR DEFECTIVE.

BNSF RESPONDER FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET OUT OF POSITION WITH APPROX 1/3 OF GASKET HANGING INSIDE MANWAY.  ALSO A SMALL PORTION OF THE GASKET WAS TORN WHEN IT WAS PINCHED BY THE CLOSURE OF THE MANWAY COVER.  GASKET WAS REPLACED IN KIND & MANWAY BOLTS TOOL TIGHTENED.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS WIPED.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: ON 8/6/02 AN ESTIMATE OF 2500-3000 GALLONS OF ASPHALT TAR WAS SPILLED AT CITGO, PERTH AMBOY, NJ SEABOARD TANK LINES, INC. WAS LOADING ASPHALT TAR INTO A TANKER WHEN OUR DRIVER STATES HE SHUT THE VALVE OFF WHICH STOPS THE FLOW OF ASPHALT TAR INTO THE TANKER.  HE NOTICED THE VALVE WAS STILL DISPENSING TAR INTO THE TANKER AND HAD BEGUN TO OVERFLOW.  AT THIS TIME, THE PRODUCT WAS SPITTING ON THE TANKER AND THE DRIVER WAS NOT ALLOWED TO CLIMB THE LADDER TO GET TO THE SHUT OFF VALVE.  HE CALLED FOR HELP AND THE PLANT MANAGER THEN USED AN EMERGENCY SHUT OFF AND THE DISPENSING OF TAR STOPPED.  OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED SEABOARD TANK LINES, INC. AND HMHTTC WAS DISPATCHED TO BEGIN CLEANUP OF THE SPILL.  HMHTTC HAS BEEN IN CONTACT WITH SEABOARD TANK LINES, INC. THROUGHOUT THE EVENING OF 8/6/02 AND ALSO ON 8/7/02 WITH UPDATES.  I SPOKE WITH THE E.H.S  MANAGER AT CITGO AND HE STATED THE DRIVER MAY HAVE THOUGHT HE SHUT OFF THE VALVE BUT IT APPEARS HE NEVER HIT THE BUTTON WITH ENOUGH FORCE TO STOP THE DISPENSING.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS USING A 3" ROPER PUMP ON OUR TRACTOR TO UNLOAD DIESEL FUEL INTO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  THE DISCHARGE PIPE HAS A "T" TO UNLOAD EASILY ON EITHER SIDE OF THE UNIT.  THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO THE STORAGE TANK FROM THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE "T"  WHEN THE LEFT SIDE CAP ON THE "T" VIBRATED LOOSE.  AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE PUMP AND AN ESTIMATED 10-15 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS DISPENSED ON THE GROUND.  DATOM PRODUCTS FROM DUNMORE, PA WAS DISPATCHED IMMEDIATELY TO THE SCENE AND BEGAN CLEANUP.  DUE TO THIS UNFORTUNATE EVENT, WE HAVE EQUIPPED EVERY UNIT WITH HART INDUSTRIES VELCRO STRAPS THAT CAN BE WRAPPED AROUND THE CAP TO PREVENT THE CAP FROM VIBRATING OFF AND THUS POSSIBLY ELIMINATING A SPILL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: A SAFETY-KLEEN MATERIALS HANDLER WAS UNLOADING A TRAILER AT A TSDF.  WHILE MANEUVERING THE FORKLIFT INSIDE A TRAILER, THE FORKLIFT PIERCED A 55 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  THE COMPROMISED CONTAINER RELEASED APPROXIMATELY TWENTY GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE TRUCK BED.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED AND CONTAINERIZED FOR STORAGE AND FUTURE DISPOSAL. THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY TWO HUNDRED POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 5756 ALBA STREET LOCATED IN LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON FORKLIFT OPERATIONS AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENT.

column42: CARBON DIOXIDE, SOLID OR DRY ICE
column168: TAXI WAS GROUND INTERRUPTED DUE TO A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT--THERE WAS NO SPILL OF ANY KIND AA FLIGHT 74, LAX-IAD, DEPARTED ONE MINUTE AFTER SCHEDULED DEPARTURE OF 2245 ON 8/07/02. THE AIRCRAFT BEGAN ITS TAXI TOWARD THE RUNWAY AT WHICH TIME THE CREW CHIEF WAS IN THE PROCESS OF CLOSING OUT THE FLIGHT WHEN HE NOTICED THAT A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT (DRY ICE COOLING FROZEN FOODS) WAS SCHEDULED AND THE PILOT HAD NOT BEEN NOTIFIED. THE AIRCRAFT WAS CALLED BACK TO THE GATE AND THE DRY ICE SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED. THE NOTIFICATION TO PILOT FORM WAS STILL ATTACHED. THE PILOT WAS GIVEN HIS COPY AND A COPY KEPT FOR THE TRIP FILE. AS A PRECAUTION, ALL SHIPMENTS WERE REVIEWED WITH THE CARGO DEPARTMENT TO VERIFY ALL WERE ACCOUNTED FOR. THE FLIGHT DEPARTED AGAIN (0010/8AUG) WHICH CAUSED AN 84 MINUTE DELAY / GROUND INTERRUPT, HENCE THIS FORM. THE EVENT WAS REVIEWED WITH THE CREW CHIEF AND HIS CREW. THE CREW CHIEF WAS RETRAINED ON PROPER FLIGHT CLOSEOUT PROCEDURES, INCLUDING THE PROPER HANDLING OF DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENTS. THE CREW CHEIF'S SUPERVISOR HELD A COUNSELLING SESSON.

WHILE AT THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION ON BAILEY ROAD IN SPENCERVILLE, OH, FREE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM A CARGO TANK. APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED IN A BUCKET FULL OF NEUTRALIZER. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO AN INTERNAL VALVE LEAK. THE CARGO TANK WAS ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE. THE BUCKET CONTAINING THE NEUTRALIZER AND FREE PRODUCT WILL BE HELD AT THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION FOR DISPOSITION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: AT 1:10 P.M. ON 8-9-02, A LOCAL FARMER WAS LEAVING THE COOPERATIVE PULLING A NURSE TANK FULL OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. AS HE TURNED A CORNER, THE NURSE TANK OVER TURNED. WHEN THE TANK HIT THE STREET, IT KNOCKED OFF THE POP-OFF VALVE AND IT'S PROTECTIVE SAFETY GUARD, CAUSING A LEAK OF PRODUCT. A NEARBY APACHE FARMERS COOPERATIVE EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. THE FIRE DEPT. USED A WATER FOG ON THE LEAK AND PLUGGED THE HOLE WHEN THE PRESSURE HAD DECREASED. WHO WAS AT FAULT IN THIS INCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION

WORN/DEFECTIVE PACKING FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE STEM, GATX 24680, AUGUST 1, 2002, SOUTH EAST DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0945 HOURS, THURSDAY, AUGUST 1, 2002, AT #7 TRACK, AT MILLVILLE YARD, MILLVILLE, NEW JERSEY, CASIE PROTANK PERSONNEL NOTED MINOR DRIP ORIGINATING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET FROM TANK CAR GATX 24680, CONTAINING HYDROCARBONS, LIQUID, N.O.S. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. INSPECTION BY CASIE PROTANK REPRESENTATIVE AND CONRAIL RISK MANAGEMENT NOTED LEAK ORIGINATING FROM PACKING/PACKING NUT FOR BOTTOM OUTLET OPERATING VALVE STEM. A REPRESENTATIVE FROM POTTS RAILCAR REPLACED PACKING. THE AREA AFFECTED BY THE SPILL WAS CLEANED BY CASIE PROTANK. CAUSE CODE 592 NARRI=5(4+1+0)X(2+0)=50

LOOSE LIQUID VALVE, UELX 78059, AUGUST 1, 2001, NORTH JERSEY DIVISION  AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HOURS, THURSDAY, AUGUST 1, 2002, AT PORT READING, NEW JERSEY, A CONRAIL FLAGMAN REPORTED TANK CAR LEAKING FROM TANK CAR UELX 78059 CONTAINING ALCOHOLS, N.O.S.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  A REPRESENTATIVE FROM REACT (AN ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR) ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THERE WAS A LOOSE LIQUID VALVE.  REACT CLEANED THREADS AND APPLIED TEFLON ON VALVES AND PLUG.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1635 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED.

column168: AT THE CARRIER'S RELAY FACILITY MATERIAL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. THE INCOMING DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR TO INVESTIGATE AND ENCOUNTERED AN OVERPOWERING ODOR. HE IMMEDIATELY MOVED TO FRESH AIR, BUT HE DID OBSERVE THAT A DRUM OF AMMONIA SOLUTION AT THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING. HE STATES THAT HE HAD STOPPED FOR A BREAK 80 MILES EARLIER AND DID NOT OBSERVE ANYTHING LEAKING THEN. HE AND THE DRIVER OF THE CONTINUING TRACTOR USED SPILL KIT MATERIALS TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE. THE CARRIER'S ON CALL HAZMAT TECHNICIAN WAS NOTIFIED AND IMMEDIATELY RETAINED A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR. THE TECHNICIAN ALSO DIRECTED THE DRIVER WHO HAD OPENED THE TRAILER TO SEEK IMMEDIATE MEDICAL ATTENTION. HE WAS TRANSPORTED TO A NEARBY FACILITY, EXAMINED, TREATED AND RELEASED. ON ARRIVAL AT THE FACILITY, THE CONTRACTOR NEUTRALIZED, THEN CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE FROM THE FACILITY LOT. THEY REMOVED AND OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM DURING  WHICH PROCESS IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LEAKER HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A NAIL IN THE TRAILER FLOOR. CARRIER DOCK PERSONNEL WERE CALLED IN TO SHIFT THE ENTIRE LOAD TO A CLEAN TRAILER. CARRIER EMPLOYEES WERE ASSISTED IN UNLOADING BY CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL IN APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT. THE TRAILER WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE TO AWAIT DECONTAMINATION. THE DRIVER HAS NOT SUFFERED ANY UNKNOWN CONTINUING IMPAIRMENT.

column168: OUR DRIVER ARRIVES AT A CUSTOMER SITE (MALLINCKRODT CHEMICAL) TO MAKE A BULK DELIVERY OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. HE CONNECTED HIS HOSE AND RECEIVED THE OK FROM THE CUSTOMER OPERATOR TO BEGAN DELIVERY. HE OPENED THE TRAILER VALVES, DELIVERY VALVES AND PUMP VALVES. HE STARTED TOWARDS THE TRACTOR WHEN HE HEARD A HISSING SOUND. HE SHUT ALL THE VALVES AND CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR AT OUR CORPORATE OFFICE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ONLY WAY TO REMOVE THE AMMONIA FROM THE PUMP WAS TO ALLOW IT TO WEATHER OFF. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT ^10 LBS OF AMMONIA WAS RELEASED. THERE WERE NO COMPLAINTS OF AMMONIA ODOR, AND NO PERSONNEL WERE EVACUATED.

EMPLOYEE PLACING PACKAGE ON SHELF ON PACKAGE CAR WAS "HIT" WITH DUST WHICH DISPERSED FROM THE FLAPS INTO EMPLOYEE'S EYES.  RESPONDER PROCESSED PACKAGE AND DETERMINED LOOSE CAP WAS THE CAUSE.  CONTENTS WERE PROCESSED THRU THE DMP PROCESS.  CLEANED AND STORED EQUIPMENT.

FOR INVESTIGATION TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT PEARL BELLO/FAA/LAX/CASFO AT 18:55(CST) ON 08/12/2002.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT THE JAHANT TRUCK STOP ON JAHANT ROAD, OFF HIGHWAY 99 SOUTH, THE DRIVER NOTICED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE FREE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE ASPHALT SURFACE.  HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KANSAS WAS CONTACTED TO COORDINATE CONTRACTOR RESPONSE.  MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL OF OAKLAND, CALIFORNIA WAS DISPATCHED TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO THE ASPHALT SURFACE AND EVAPORATED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A NAIL ON THE PALLET.  NO CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE REQUIRED AND NO WASTE WAS GENERATED.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM.  THE OVERPACK DRUM WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TERMINAL IN WEST SACRAMENTO, CALIFORNIA, WHERE IT WILL BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE IN THE TERMINAL YARD, TERMINAL PERSONNEL DETECTED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGE FAILURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL B PROTECTION, ABSORBENTS PADS, AMPHOMAG, A BROOM AND A SHOVEL.  THE CLEANUP SUITS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM AND WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THERE IS NO REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES  OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUEST AND RECEIVED.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE COMING FROM THE PACKAGE WAS NOTICED.  THE ITEM WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL TWO PLASTIC CONTAINERS.  APPARENTLY THE BOTTOM SEAM ON BOTH OF THE UNITS FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACE INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE LOADING, ONE LEAKING, THIRTY POUND METAL CYLINDER WAS DISCOVERED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED GLOVES TO CLOSE THE VALVE ON THE CYLINDER.  THERE WAS NO CLEANUP NECESSARY.  THE CYLINDER WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED.

column168: THE TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RICE YARD, IN WAYCROSS, GA, REPORTED THAT THERE WAS AN ODOR IN THE VICINITY OF 2 TANK CARS IN THE CLASSIFICATION YARD.  ALL EMPLOYEES WERE REMOVED FROM THE AREA AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  THE TRAINMASTER INSPECTED THE CARS AND REPORTED HE COULD DETECT ONLY A FAINT ODOR IN THE AREA.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CHECKED THE CARS WITH A COMBUSTIBLE GAS METER BY PLACING THE PROBE THROUGH THE UNLOADING PORTS IN THE DOMES OF THE CARS.  THEY OBTAINED A SMALL READING ON THE METER INSIDE THE DOME OF GATX 40712.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS SATISFIED THAT THERE WAS NO DANGER OF FIRE AND THEY DEPARTED.  THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THROUGH CHEMTREC.  CSX TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT CALLED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO MAKE REPAIRS.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS LOOSE ALLOWING VAPORS TO ESCAPE AROUND THE GAUGING ROD.  THEY TIGHTENED THE PACKING GLAND NUT AND THE VAPOR LEAK STOPPED.  MR. GIOVANNI WITH EOTT ENERGY WAS ADVISED OF THE PROBLEM WITH THE CAR.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DRUM WAS DAMAGED WHILE ENROUTE TO THE HARTFORD CT CCX TERMINAL. DAMAGE WAS CAUSED BY SHIFTING OF IMPROPERLY LOADED FREIGHT DURING TRANSIT. FREIGHT LOADED ON RACKS ABOVE H/M DRUMS FELL ONTO DRUMS CAUSING PUNCTURE AT BASE OF ONE DRUM. THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED BY DRIVER AS TRAILER WAS BEING DROPPED AT DESTINATION TERMINAL. DRIVER NOTICE LIQUID LEAKING FROM FLOOR OF TRAILER. DRIVER NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR AND LOADING MANIFEST WAS REVIEWED TO DETERMINE IF H/M WAS INVOLVED. AREA WAS SECURED UNTIL TYPE OF HAZARD AND LEVEL OF RESPONSE COULD BE DETERMINED. ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS THEN SPREAD TO CONTAIN LEAKAGE. AREA SAFETY SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED, AND BOTH CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE CONTACTED FOR PRODUCT DETAILS AND CLEAN UP PROCEDURES. MATERIAL HAZARD WAS DETERMINED TO BE MINIMAL, AND SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS LOST, LESS THAN 5 GALLONS. DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUM. SWEEPINGS AND ALL RELATED MATERIALS WERE CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. BALANCE OF DAMAGED MATERIAL TO BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR REPACKAGING. SITUATION TO BE REVIEWED WITH ALL RESPONSIBLE TO AVOID REOCCURRENCE.

DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AFTER OTHER FREIGHT HAD BEEN LOADED BEHIND IT. IT LOOKS DUE TO FORKLIFT DAMAGE. DRUM WAS NO PROTECTED BY DUNNAGE. DUNNAGE WILL BE USED TO PROTECT FUTURE SHIPMENTS OF THIS KIND.

WHEN DRIVER ARRIVED BACK AT TERMINAL. HE OPENED THE DOOR & NOTICED WHITE POWDER ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION IT APPEARED THAT WHEN HIS LAST CUSTOMER LOADED HIS FREIGHT. HE PUSHED A PRIOR LOADED SKID OF FIBER DRUMS FORWARD CAUSING ONE OF THE FIBER DRUMS TO STRIKE A LOAD BAR. THE CONTACT WITH THE LOAD BAR CAUSED THE FIBER DRUM TO PUNCTURE CAUSING ABOUT 6 MEASURING CUPS TO SPILL UNTO TRAILER FLOOR.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURED. WHILE UNLOADING, AN ODOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE TRAILER. TWO EMPLOYEES WERE EXPOSED BY INHALATION BUT DID NOT SEEK MEDICAL ATTENTION. THE TERMINAL WAS EVACUATED. HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KS WAS CONTACTED TOO COORDINATED CLEANUP. MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL OF OAKLAND, CA RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL OF OAKLAND, CA PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL B PROTECTION. UPON INVESTIGATION BY MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE, FIVE HUNDRED MILLILITER BOTTLE WAS BROKEN. AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF FUMES WERE RELEASED. THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO USED PACKAGING, THE BOTTLES LOOKED OLD AND USED. MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL OF OAKLAND, CA TOOK THE BROKEN BOTTLE AND PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND PLACED THEM INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM. MORGAN ENVIRONMENTAL OF OAKLAND, CA WILL DISPOSE OF THE RECOVERY DRUM. LARRY KOENEKE OF ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. WAS CONTACTED TO DISCUSS THE EMPLOYEE EXPOSURES AND REPORTING. ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE CONTACTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ON THE DATE I WAS ASSIGNED TO PROCESS CONTENTS OF THE SALVAGE DRUM VIA UPS DMP BECAUSE UPS CANNOT IDENTIFY THE SHIPPER TO RETURN IT TO, THE UPS SHIPPING PAPERS WERE OBLITERATED, PROBABLY BY THE ORIGINAL LEAKER. NUMEROUS ATTEMPTS TO IDENTIFY & CONTACT THE SHIPPER PROVED UNSUCCESSFUL. VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE VARIOUS LABELS ON THE DRUM INDICATE IMPROPER PROCESSING BY THE HUB WHERE THIS WAS PROCESSED. THE PACKAGE PROGRESS MUST BE TRACKED TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE ERROR & THE RESPONDER(S) RESPONSIBLE NEED TO BE RETRAINED. THE DRUM WAS NON-COMPLIANT WITH DOT, EPA AND OSHA AS THE SHIPPING PAPER WAS NOT LEGIBLE & THE DRUM SHOULD NEVER HAVE MADE IT THIS FAR. IF PROPER PROCEDURE HAD BEEN FOLLOWED THE CHEMICAL WOULD HAVE BEEN DISPOSED OF AT THE HUB WHEE THE DAMAGE WAS DISCOVERED.

RESPONDING TO A REPORT OF A LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE YELLOW SLIDE, I FOUND THIS PACKAGE ISOLATED IN AN EMPTY. LOCATION ON THE SLIDE. QUESTIONING THE PRELOADER AND HIS SUPERVISOR(DOUG) I LEARNED THAT DOUG HAD MOVED IT AWAY FROM THE REST OF THE BOXES, THEN WIPED THE SPILL OFF OF THE SLIDE WITH PAPER TOWELS WHICH HE THEN THREW INTO A TRASH CAN. I CONFRONTED THEM ABOUT "DON'T TOUCH..." THEN RETRIEVED THE CONTAMINATED PAPER TOWELS FOR DMP DISPOSAL..I NEXT SPOKE WITH DOUG'S SUPERVISOR GARY SUPINSKI ABOUT THIS BEING A BREECH OF SAFETY. DOUG WAS REPRIMANDED BY THE SORT MANAGER JOE O'HARA. I COMPLETED A UPS FORM HM-10 BECAUSE THERE WAS NO CUSHIONING USED BY THE SHIPPER BETWEEN THE CAN AND THE CARTON.

THIS RAILCAR WAS OBSERVED HISSING BY THE AFOFINA CORP. AFOTINA NOTIFIED GEISMAR YARD.  THE SHIPPER, PIONEER, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE WAS DETERMINED TO THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  A "C" KIT WAS INSTALLED OVER THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE WHICH SECURED THE RELEASE AT 2155 HOURS.  THE RAILCAR WAS MOVED BACK INTO PIONEER CHEMICAL COMPANY AND THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE WAS DISASSEMBLED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE BREAKING PIN IN THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE HAD BROKEN. THE WRONG BREAKING PIN WAS INSTALLED IN THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE.  THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE WAS ASSEMBLED AS A 225 LB DEVICE INSTEAD OF THE REQUIRED 375 LB. DEVICE.
FOUND VALVE LEAKING ON CAR.  US ENVIRONMENTAL CO REPLACED DEFECTIVE VALVE AND SCRUBBED CAR DOWN TO REMOVE SPILLED PRODUCT ON CAR SURFACE.  CAR BACK IN SERVICE AT 1:30 PM.

column14: ON I-5 NORTH AT MARYSVILLE WEI
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT THE MARYSVILLE WEIGH STATION THE USF REDDAWAY DRIVER OBSERVED FREE PRODUCT INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE MARYSVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  CLEAN UP WAS PERFORMED BY FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. OF SEATTLE, WASHINGTON.  FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. PLACED A PUNCTURED FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM OF PRODUCT INTO A EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON METAL OVERPACK DRUM.  FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO RECOVER THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AND ASPHALT SURFACE.  FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. PLACED THE USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL INTO AN EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  ONE EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON OVERPACK DRUM AND ONE EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUM WERE TRANSPORTED TO USF REDDAWAY IN KENT, WASHINGTON FOR DISPOSAL COORDINATION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.

THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN 4 PLY PLASTIC BAGS AND TAKEN TO A SECURE AREA.  THE DANGEROUS GOODS OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED, AND THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD FOR INSPECTION BY AN FAA REPRESENTATIVE.

THE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO AN AREA OF THE SORTATION FACILITY WHERE THE SUPERVISOR HAD RESTRICTED TRAFFIC AROUND A FORKLIFT AND A SHIPMENT IT HAD RUN OVER.  THE MATERIAL WAS IDENTIFIED BY ITS ACCOMPANYING PAPERWORK AND THE SHIPMENT BAGGED, ALONG WITH THE SUPPLIES USED TO CLEAN UP THE AREA.  THE BAGS WERE THEN TAKEN TO THE HAZARDOUS WASTE AREA AT THE FACILITY AND DRUMMED.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED OUT OF A TRAILER ON THE MORNING PRE-LOAD. IT WAS NOTICED THAT IT WAS LEAKING SO THE BELT WAS STOPPED. I REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE BELT AND CLEANED UP ANY REMAINING RESIDUE ON THE BELT. AFTER THE SORT WAS OVER I DISPOSED OF THE REMAINING MATERIALS THROUGH OUR DAMAGED MATERIALS PROCESSING PROGRAM. THIS PROBLEM HAS BECOME A COMMON OCCURRENCE WITH THIS PARTICULAR SHIPPER. TYPICALLY THEY WILL PUT FOUR 1-GALLON BOTTLES IN A BOX WITHOUT ANY PACKAGING TO PROTECT THEM, THEN THEY TAKE NO MEASURES TO INSURE THAT THE CAPS ARE SECURE AND WON'T LEAK.

AFTER FILLING CUSTOMER TRUCK WITH FUEL, FUEL OIL WAS FOUND UNDER THE TRUCK. CUSTOMER ALLEGED WE OVERFILLED THE TANK HOWEVER NO SPILL OF 20 GALLONS WAS DETECTED BY OUT DRIVER WHILE ON THE CUSTOMER'S PROPERTY. THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF OUR HOSE, NOZZLE OR PUMP.

THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY. ONE DRUM OF WASTE HAD TO BE SHIPPED FOR DISPOSAL.
REAR VALVE LEFT OPEN AND PRODUCT RAN OUT WHEN STARTED LOADING PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN CONTAINMENT. PRODUCT WAS PUMPED INTO TOTE AND DISPOSED OF. NRC 620641

DRIVER WAS DELIVERING KEROSENE TO A 10,000 GALLON UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. DRIVER MISTAKENLY THOUGHT HE HAD ENOUGH ROOM IN THE TANK TO DELIVER ALL THE PRODUCT HE HAD ON HIS TRUCK. WHEN TANK REACHED IT'S CAPACITY, PRODUCT WAS FORCED FROM A REMOTE FILL, CAUSING A 50-60 GALLON KEROSENE SPILL. FIRE DEPT RESPONDED AND SPREAD SAND ON THE SPILL. COMPANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM CLEANED UP REMAINDER OF SPILL. PA DEP. NOTIFIED. FIVE 55 GALLON SEALED DRUMS WITH CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WILL BE PICKED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY AQUA-TEX INC, HAMMONTON, N.J.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DURING TRANSPORTATION TO OUR LA SALLE TERMINAL, OTHER FREIGHT SHIFTED INTO A DRUM CAUSING IT TO LEAK OUT THE DRUM AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND IS BEING HELD FOR DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING AT OUR PARSONS DOCK A FORKLIFT BLADE PUNCTURED ONE DRUM CAUSING IT TO LEAK. THE DRUM WAS REPAIRED WITH A METAL PATCH AND IS BEING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR REPACKING OF THE REMAINDER OF PRODUCT.

A CHLORINE RAILCAR CONNECTED TO THE DPC ENTERPRISES' PIPING SYSTEM TRANSFER HOSE RUPTURED WHILE UNDER PRESSURE FOR PACKAGING OPERATIONS. DPC PLANT PERSONNEL ACTIVATED THE ALARM AND IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED THE AREA. PLANT MANAGER CONTACTED 9-1-1 TO REPORT INCIDENT AND REQUEST ASSISTANCE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVES AND EVACUATES DPC NEIGHBORING BUSINESSES AND RESIDENTS AS WELL AS ESTABLISHES COMMAND POST. JEFFERSON COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM AND DPC PERSONNEL RESPOND AND STOP THE CHLORINE RELEASE. INCIDENT INVESTIGATION STILL ON-GOING.

APPROX 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED.  DRIVER STARTED TO LOAD AND NOTICED THE DRIP BARREL OVERFLOWING.  THE DRAIN VALVE ON THE TRAILER WAS LEFT OPEN RESULTING IN A SPILLAGE.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY MISSION.  THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN A WRITTEN WARNING AND COUNSELING ON PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES.  THE LOAD WAS NOT COMPLETED DUE TO SPILL.  NO SHIPPER/CONSIGNEE INFORMATION AVAILABLE.

CUSTOMER WAS UNLOADING LIQUID TRANSPORT TANK.  THEY USED THEIR HOSE AND AIR TO BLOW LOAD OFF INTO THEIR TANK.  WHEN LIQUID TRANSPORT TANK WENT EMPTY. THE AIR FROM EMPTY TANK PUSHED PRODUCT OUT OF TOP OF CUSTOMER TANK. SPILLING 20 GALLONS INTO DIKE AREA.  THE CUSTOMER TOOK FULL RESPONSIBILITY OF THE SPILL AND CLEANED THE SPILL UP.

column168: FGT WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE CENTER WHERE A SMALL RUB WAS LOCATED ON ONE OF THE BUCKETS.  THE BUCKET WAS TILTED TO AVOID SPILL AND CONTAINED.  TO AVOID THIS IN THE FUTURE, PLYWOOD OR CARDBOARD SHOULD BE PLACED ON THE SKID BEFORE THE BUCKETS ARE PLACED ON THEM.  A PROTRUDING NAIL WAS THE CAUSE OF THE RUB.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND A MSDS WAS OBTAINED ON THE MATERIAL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE GOING NORTH ON BUSINESS 121 IN LEWISVILLE, APPROACHING A TRAFFIC SIGNAL.  LIGHT TURNED RED AND DRIVER TURNED RIGHT TO AVOID A CAR PULLING OUT.  VEHICLE OVERTURNED ONTO LEFT SIDE CAUSING TANK TO RUPTURE WHEN IT STRUCK THE CONCRETE CURB.  SPILLED FUEL WAS CONTAINED IN DRAINAGE AREA. CLEANUP WAS CONDUCTED BY EAGLE CONSTRUCTION.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: TRAILER # 615-8208 CONTAINING THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION WAS PUT TO THE DOCK TO UNLOAD.  IT WAS NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A CLEAR LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND THE SHIPMENT SKID WAS BROKEN DOWN TO FIND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THERE WERE ABOUT TEN 5 GALLON PAILS ON THE SKID, ONLY ONE OF THEM WAS DAMAGED.  BETWEEN THE SKID AND FIVE GALLON PAILS WAS A SHEET OF CORRUGATED ABOUT AN INCH THICK.  THERE WERE TWO NAILS THAT WERE PROTRUDING FROM THE SKID, THAT DURING TRANSPORT WORKED THROUGH HE CARDBOARD AND PUNCTURED THE PAIL, WE CLEANED UP THE RELEASED MATERIAL WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED THE OIL DRY, THE PUNCTURED PAIL AND ONE OTHER PIECE OF THE SHIPMENT THAT WAS CONTAMINATED IN AN OVERSIZED 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SALVAGE DRUM IS ON A SALVAGE DRUM IN A STORAGE TRAILER AT NASHVILLE CON-WAY SERVICE CENTER, 40 NANCE LANE NASHVILLE TN 37210.
column172: Metal pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: A HAZ MAT LEAK WAS FOUND DURING THE UNLOADING OF A TRAILER.  A HAZ MAT SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE.  ON ARRIVAL THE TEAM FOUND TWO 5 GALLON PAILS OF DICHLOROMETHANE, 6.1, UN1593, PGIII.  THE PAILS HAD STARTED LEAKING DUE TO THE WEIGHT OF THE PAILS LOADED ON THE TOP.  THE HAZ MAT CREW SECURED AND CLEANED THE CONTAMINATED AREA.  THE TWO LEAKING PAILS WERE PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK, LABELED, AND PLACED BACK ONTO THE TRUCK FOR SHIPMENT.  THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENTS GENERATED FROM THE CLEAN UP WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM ALONG WITH THE PPE FOR DISPOSAL.  THE 55 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE WAS TAKEN OFF SITE TO BE DISPOSED OF.

column168: DRIVER STARTED THE UNLOADING PROCESS AND WAS ASK TO SWITCH TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO UNLOAD THE REMAINING AMOUNT OF PRODUCT.  WHEN THE DRIVER SWITCHED FROM THE CENTER TO THE REAR THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN THE ELBOW OF THE UNLOADING LINE CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO SPILL. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY THE PLANT PERSONNEL AND THE DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING WITHOUT ANY FURTHER INCIDENT.  DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER PROCEDURES AND SPILL PREVENTION.

A CSXT TRAIN CREW SWITCHING IN THE EAST CHICAGO, IN, YARD OBSERVED UTLX 130452, A LOAD OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID, EMITTING VAPORS FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AND WETNESS ON THE TOP OF THE CAR.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE (ER) CONTRACTOR TO ASSESS THE CAR AND TO MAKE APPROPRIATE REPAIRS TO HALT ANY RELEASE.  THE ER CONTRACTOR ADVISED THAT THERE WAS LIQUID PRODUCT ON THE TOP OF THE PRODUCT RELIEF DEVICE, AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRODUCT RELIEF DEVICE AND THE MANWAY.  THE ER CONTRACTOR INSPECTED BOTH THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS AND THE MANWAY COVER GASKET AND THEY WERE IN PROPER CONDITION.  NO OTHER SOURCE OF LEAKAGE WAS OBSERVED.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE PRODUCT RELIEF DEVICE ACTIVATED.  THE SHIPPER WAS INFORMED OF THE FINDINGS.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: A CITIZEN COMPLAINT TO THE LAKE TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPARTMENT OF AN ODOR COMING FROM THE CSX TRANSPORTATION YARD IN WALBRIDGE, OH., PROMPTED  CSXT TO INITIATE AN INVESTIGATION.  CSXT DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE (ER) CONTRACTOR TO TRY AND IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR AND HALT THE EMISSION OF ODOROUS VAPORS, IF POSSIBLE.  THE ER CONTRACTOR OBSERVED EVIDENCE OF A RECENT SPLASH ON TANK CAR ACFX 77602.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION THE ER CONTRACTOR FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS THE INCORRECT SIZE.  THE ER CONTRACTOR REPLACED THE GASKET WITH THE CORRECT SIZE GASKET.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE FINDINGS.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: A CSXT CREW WAS SWITCHING CARS IN THE LONDON, KY YARD WHEN NW 176949, A LOADED COVERED HOPPER CAR OF AMMONIUM NITRATE, ROLLED AWAY FROM THE CREW. THE CAR TRAVELED TO THE SOUTH END OF THE YARD WHERE IT ENCOUNTERED A DERAILER, A SAFETY MECHANISM USED TO PREVENT UNAUTHORIZED MOVEMENT OF RAIL EQUIPMENT ON TO THE MAIN LINE TRACKS.  WHEN THE CAR HIT THE DERAILER IT OVERTURNED.  THE LOADING HATCHES ON THE TOP OF THE CAR OPENED AND APPROXIMATELY 40 TONS OF MATERIAL SPILLED INTO TOWN BRANCH CREEK, A TRIBUTARY OF THE LITTLE LAUREL RIVER.  HEAVY PRECIPITATION IN THE AREA AT THE TIME OF THE DERAILMENT HAD SWOLLEN THE CREEK OUT OF ITS BANKS AND APPROXIMATELY 35 TONS OF MATERIAL WAS SWEPT DOWNSTREAM.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS ABLE TO EXCAVATE 5 TONS OF SPILLED PRODUCT FROM THE CREEK BANKS AND BOTTOM.  THE CAR WAS UP RIGHTED WITHOUT FURTHER LOSS OF PRODUCT.  CSXT CONTRACTORS AND CONSULTANTS WORKED WITH STATE AND LOCAL OFFICIALS TO MONITOR THE AFFECTED WATER AS IT MOVED DOWNSTREAM.

DRIVER ONCE AGAIN LOOKED AT HIS RIGHT MIRROR TO CHECK FOR A CLEAR LANE WHEN HE NOTICED THE TRAILER SKIDDING OUT TO HIS RIGHT.  NEXT THING DRIVER KNOWS IS HE IS FLIPPED OVER ON RIGHT SIDE SKIDDING ON ITS SIDE.  WHEN VEHICLE CAME TO A COMPLETE STOP, BOTH DRIVER AND CO-DRIVER EXITED VEHICLE BY DRIVER DOOR. THE TRUCK SKIDDED ON ITS RIGHT SIDE SCRAPING TANK DOWN TO INNER LINING RELEASING LOAD.  PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AT A  RATE SO FAST DRIVER HAD NO TIME TO ATTEMPT TO CONTAIN.  AS PRODUCT SPREAD THROUGHOUT THE SB LANES OF I-110 IT DRAINED OFF THROUGH SEWER SYSTEM.  ACTI WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED AND WAS TASKED WITH THE CONTAINMENT EFFORT, AS WELL AS THE RECOVERY OF ALL RELEASED PRODUCT.

THE CARRIER DOCK WAS OFF-LOADING THE TRAILER, WHEN THEY DAMAGED THREE PAILS.  THEY WERE ATTEMPTING TO OFF-LOAD A ROW OF PAILS IN BOXES, WHEN THREE OF THEM FELL.TO THE FLOOR.  WHEN THE PAILS HIT THE FLOOR, THE LIDS POPPED OFF AND LEAKED ALL OF THE PRODUCT INTO THE BOXES.  FIFTEEN GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED, WHICH WAS HELD BY THE CARDBOARD BOXES HOUSING THE PAILS.  THE DAMAGED PAILS WERE PLACED IN AN OVERPACK AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  DUE TO THE FACT THE PAILS WERE PACKAGED IN CARDBOARD BOXES, THERE WAS NO PRODUCT SPILLAGE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.

THE CARRIER DOCK WAS OFF-LOADING THE TRAILER, WHEN THEY DAMAGED ONE DRUM. THEY WERE OFF-LOADING A SKID IN FRONT OF THE DRUM AND FORKED THE DRUM WHEN THE DOCK PUSHED THEY FORK ALL THE WAY THROUGH THE SKID.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT, BEFORE THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK AND DUE TO THE RAPID EVAPORATION OF THE PRODUCT, NO CLEAN-UP OF THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS NEEDED.  THE OVERPACKED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

column168: THE CARRIER DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON 1-495 WHEN HE WAS FLAGGED DOWN BY ANOTHER CARRIER DRIVER AND TOLD HE HAD SOMETHING LEAKING.  THEY STOPPED THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY, NEAR TOLEDO, OHIO AND CHECKED THE FREIGHT IN THE TRAILER.  THEY SAW ONE LEAKING FROM A FORK HOLE ON IT'S SIDE.  USING PROPER PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, THE DRIVERS TURNED THE DRUM ON IT'S SIDE TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE HAZMAT DEPARTMENT CONTACTED A LOCAL CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE TO OVERPACK THE DRUM, CLEAN THE TRAILER FLOOR AND CLEAN THE GROUND OUTSIDE THE TRAILER.  AS THE DRIVER AWAITED THE CONTRACTOR, THE SYLVANIA FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON SCENE ALONG WITH THE OHIO STATE POLICE.  THEY INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO FOLLOW THEM TO FOLLOW THEM TO A REMOTE AREA OFF OF THE HIGHWAY, SO THE CONTRACTOR HAD ROOM TO WORK AND THE HIGHWAY WASN'T SHUT DOWN.  HAZMAT RELAYED THE CHANGE OF LOCATION TO THE CONTRACTOR.  THE CONTRACTOR OVERPACKED THE DRUM, DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER AND WENT TO THE ORIGINAL SCENE AND DECONTAMINATED THE GROUND NEXT TO THE HIGHWAY.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

AS THE FACILITY'S PERSONNEL HAVE NO WAY TO CONDUCT A CLEAN UP OF THE SPILLAGE, THE CARRIER RETAINED THE SERVICES OF A SPILL CONTRACTOR. THE OVERPACK DRUM WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY TO AWAIT DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

column168: CARRIER'S INDEPENDENT CONTRACTOR DRIVER CALLED FROM A TRUCK STOP TO REPORT THAT THERE IS INK LEAKING ONTO THE GROUND FROM HIS TRAILER. AFTER OPENING THE TRAILER DOOR HE COULD SEE THAT TWO DRUMS APPEAR TO BE LEAKING. IN ADDITION, ALL OF THE DRUMS IN THE SHIPMENT HAVE PRODUCT ON THEIR HEADS. THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO PLACE MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT ON THE GROUND TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE. THE SPECIALIST THEN RETAINED THE SERVICES OF A CONTRACTOR TO PROCEED TO THE SITE TO MITIGATE THE SITUATION. THE CONTRACTOR'S PERSONNEL PLACED THE KNOWN LEAKING DRUMS INTO SALVAGE DRUMS. AS THEY UNLOADED THE REST OF THE SHIPMENT THEY DETERMINED THAT TWO OTHER DRUMS HAD SIMILAR LEAKS. THOSE WERE ALSO PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS. THE CONTRACTOR TIGHTENED ALL BUNGS AND CLEANED THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE DRIVER THEN CONTINUED ON HIS WAY.

AT AN INTERMEDIATE STOP THE CARRIER'S DRIVER OBSERVED LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  HE FOUND A DRUM THAT APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN HIT AND WAS LEAKING FROM TWO FORK HOLES.  IN ADDITION, A PIECE OF 2X4 THAT HAD BEEN NAILED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR AS A SECUREMENT DEVICE WAS BADLY DAMAGED.  THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS DRIPPING OUT OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE GROUND FROM SEVERAL POINTS.  THE DRIVER USED MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO CAPTURE AND CONTAIN ALL OF THE LEAKAGE.  THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST RETAINED A CONTRACTOR TO PROCEED TO THE SITE.  THE CONTRACTOR PUMPED THE REMAINING LIQUID FROM THE DAMAGED DRUM INTO A NEW DRUM, THEN CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THEY DECONTAMINATED THE AREAS UNDER THE TRAILER WHERE THE MATERIAL HAD LEAKED OUT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY TO AWAIT DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON AUGUST 15, 2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 A.M., A PETROLEUM TRANSPORT TANKER OPERATED BY MCCOMBS OIL & PROPANE LEFT THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE NORTH BOUND LANES OF U.S. HIGHWAY 321 AND TRAVELED DOWN THE ROADWAY EMBANKMENT BEFORE COMING TO REST IN A SMALL CREEK. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED APPROXIMATELY 1,000 FEET SOUTH OF THE RIVER ROAD EXIT (EXIT NUMBER 41) (FIGURE 1). THE TANKER WAS REPORTEDLY CARRYING 7,926 GALLONS OF OFF ROAD LOW SULFUR DIESEL FUEL PLUS THE FUEL IN THE TRUCK'S SADDLE FUEL TANKS. THE TANKER WAS PUMPED OUT BY 10:00 A.M. AND THEN REMOVED FROM THE CREEK. THE CAB OF THE TRUCK AND TANKER CAME TO REST IN A SMALL CREEK. THE SPILL OCCURRED AT THE HEAD WATERS OF AN UNNAMED TRIBUTARY TO HENRY FORK (FIGURE 1). THE CONFLUENCE OF THE TRIBUTARY AND HENRY FORK IS APPROXIMATELY 2.8 MILES SOUTHEAST OF THE SITE. HENRY FORK FLOWS SOUTH APPROXIMATELY TWO MILES WERE IT JOIN WITH JACOB FORK TO FORM THE SOUTH FORK OF THE CATAWBA RIVER. ONCE EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT SERVICES (EMS) ARRIVED AT THE SITE, A TEMPORARY EARTHEN DAM AND UNDER FLOW DAM WERE CONSTRUCTED TO CAPTURE ANY FUEL LEAKING INTO THE CREEK. THE EARTHEN AND UNDER FLOW DAMS WERE CONSTRUCTED APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET AND 300 FEET DOWN STREAM OF THE IMPACT SITE, RESPECTIVELY (FIGURE 2). TWO SETS OF BOOMS WERE INSTALLED ACROSS THE CREEK APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET ND 300 FEET DOWN STREAM OF THE UNDER FLOW DAM. SMALL POCKETS OF FUEL WERE CLEANED WITH ABSORBENT PADS. THE LEAK WAS SMALL, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 1,100 GALLONS OF FUEL. AN ADDITIONAL 100 GALLONS OF FUEL WAS LOOSE FROM THE SADDLE TANKS. THE FUEL THAT WAS CAPTURED BEHIND THE DAMS AND BOOMS WAS VACUUMED INTO A TANKER TRUCK, FOR OFF SITE DISPOSAL. APPROXIMATELY 800 GALLONS OF FUEL WERE RECOVERED THROUGH VACUUMING EFFORTS AND THE REMAINING FUEL WAS COLLECTED IN BOOMS AND PADS. BY 6:00 PM THE EVENING OF AUGUST 15, 2002, THE MAJORITY OF THE FUEL HAD BEEN REMOVED. THE DAMS, BOOMS, AND PADS WERE LEFT IN PLACE. THE TRANSPORTATION MANIFESTS FOR THE LIQUID ARE INCLUDED IN APPENDIX A. PHOTOGRAPHS OF THE ACCIDENT AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE MEASURES ARE INCLUDED IN APPENDIX B.

column168: ON AUGUST 26, 2002 @ 19:30, THE 14:00 HR TRAIN CREW WAS BRINGING IN A TRAIN THAT CONSISTED OF (124) CARS FROM THE UP. THE TRAIN WAS MADE UP OF (26) LOADS AND (98) EMPTIES. THE CAUSES OF THE DERAILMENT WAS THE MAKE UP OF THE TRAIN. THE LOADS, ALL (26), WERE IN THE MIDDLE OF THE EMPTIES WITH THE DIFFERENCE OF GRADE AND SLACK OF THE TRAIN, AND THE WAY THE CARS WERE BLOCKED, THIS SET THE TRAIN TO DERAIL. ONE EMPTY CAR DERAILED FIRST THEN THE LOADS FOLLOWED BEHIND IT. THERE WERE (3) CARS,  THESE BEING ACFX 81703, ACFX 83368, ACFX 84774, AND (6) MORE THAT DERAILED. TOTAL PRODUCT RELEASED FROM THE (3) CARS THAT WERE ON THEIR SIDE DID NOT EXCEED (5) GALLONS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WERE CALLED IMMEDIATELY TO SECURE THE AREA AND COMMERCE CLEAN UP.

column168: SEE APPENDIX I: ON AUGUST 05, 2002 AT 15:15, TRAIN 515-05 DEPARTED KENWOOD YARD VIA N/E CROSSOVER AND WAS NOTIFIED TO STOP MOVEMENT AS TWO CARS HAD DERAILED. ALBANY FIRE DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED, UPON THEIR ARRIVAL THEY PLACED A CATCH BASIN UNDERNEATH CAR AND FOAM APPLIED TO CONTROL EXPLOSIVE VAPORS.  SHIPPER EXXON/MOBIL ADVISED AND ON SITE WITH TWO ER CONTRACTORS, MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL AND ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES & PRODUCTS. CPR ER CONTRACTOR OP-TECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ALSO MOBILIZED AND ON SITE.  CPR FIELD MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS/EMERGENCY RESPONSE ALSO DISPATCHED TO SITE.  CAR GATX 66348 SUSTAINED A STRESS CRACK AT BOTTOM OF SLOPE SHEET DUE TO WHEEL L-2 CONTACTING AND INDENTING TANK, CAR TRANSSHIPPED AND BOTH CARS RERAILED WITHOUT INCIDENT.

column168: THE FOLLOWING DESCRIBES THE EVENTS ASSOCIATED WITH THE SMALL SPILL FROM THE MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSPORT DUMP TRAILER ON MARCH 7TH, 2002.  THE MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSPORT DRIVER CHECKED THE DUMP TRAILER AT ANNA OHIO FOR LEAKAGE.  THIS WAS AT MILE MARKER 100 AT INTERSTATE 75 NORTH. THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE AT THIS POINT.  SOMEWHERE BETWEEN THE MILE MAKER 100 AND MILE MARKER 189, A INTERSTATE 75 COMMUTER'S CAR CONTACTED SOME LIQUID FROM THE DUMP TRAILER.  THE COMMUTER CONTACTED THE OHIO STATE PATROL.  THE OHIO STATE PATROLMEN PULLED THE DUMP TRAILER OVER AT MILE MARKER 189 ON INTERSTATE 75.  THE DUMP TRAILER WAS LEAKING AT THIS POINT AND HAD DRIPPED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD WHEN STOPPED.  THE HIGHWAY PATROLMAN ASKED FOR THE MANIFEST AND THEN PROCEEDED TO SHUT DOWN BOTH LANES OF INTERSTATE 75.  WITHIN 30 MINUTES A WOOD COUNTY EPA OFFICIAL ARRIVED AT THE SCENE.  THE EPA OFFICIAL ADVISED THE STATE PATROLMEN TO RE-OPEN INTERSTATE 75 WHICH THE PATROLMAN DID.  THIS WAS DUE TO THE SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL THAT ACTUALLY LEAKED ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND BENIGN NATURE OF THE LEAKED MATERIAL.  CONCURRENTLY THE DRIVER HAD CONTACTED THE TREATMENT, STORAGE AND DISPOSAL FACILITY WHERE THE MATERIAL HAD BEEN GENERATED.  THE PLANT MANAGER PROCEEDED TO NOTIFY THE OHIO EPA EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER, NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND WOOD COUNTY LOCAL EMERGENCY PLANNING COUNCIL OF THE SITUATION.  EQ WAS CONTRACTED TO MITIGATE THE LEAK AND PERFORM ANY NECESSARY CLEAN UP.  AT MILE MARKER 189, A EQ EMPLOYEE ARRIVED TO MITIGATE THE LEAK FROM THE DUMP TRAILER.  THE BACK OF THE DUMP TRAILER WAS MIXED WITH OIL DRY AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE DRIVER WAS THEN ADVISED TO MAKE A U TURN AT EXIT 192 AND THEN PROCEED SOUTH ON INTERSTATE 75 BACK TO THE EQ SATELLITE STATION AT EXIT 187.  WHILE IN TRANSIT, AND AFTER STARTING SOUTH ON INTERSTATE 75, THE TRAILER BEGAN TO LEAK AGAIN AT MILE MARKER 191 ON INTERSTATE 75 SOUTH.  BY THAT TIME A CONTRACTED HAZMAT TEAM HAD ARRIVED FROM EQ'S BELLEVILLE MICHIGAN FACILITY.  THE INTERIOR AND EXTERIOR OF THE GATE WAS SEALED WITH FOAM AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE DUMP TRAILER PROCEEDED TO THE EQ SATELLITE STATION AT EXIT 187 ON INTERSTATE 75 SOUTH.  A DOT OFFICIAL HAD ARRIVED AT THIS POINT AND CLEARED THE DUMP TRAILER TO PROCEED TO ITS DISPOSAL POINT AT BELLEVILLE MICHIGAN.  THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT BELLEVILLE MICHIGAN AND SPENT THE NIGHT.  THE NEXT MORNING THE MATERIAL WAS DUMPED AT THE BELLEVILLE EQ DISPOSAL FACILITY.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT AT AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANKS CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S AMPTHILL, VA PLANT. THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S.  THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATION, 49 CFR.

WHILE BEING HANDLED AT THE AA BAGRROM AREA AT MIA, EMPLOYEES SMELLED AN ALCOHOL TYPE ODOR EMANATING FROM A GREEN MILITARY TYPE CANVAS DUFFLE BAG WHICH ARRIVED FROM CHICAGO, IL ON FLIGHT AA 795 AND FINAL DESTINATION WAS TEGUCIGALPA, HONDURAS ON FLIGHT AA 953. BAGROOM ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR WAS SUMMONED AND AFTER INVESTIGATION FOUND ONE 16FL OZ BOTTLE OF ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL BOTTLE WITH A LOOSE CAP AND ITS CONTENT SPILLED. ALL OF THE 16 FL OZ OF ALCOHOL WERE ABSORBED BY THE PASSENGERS BELONGINGS. CLEAN UP WAS HANDLED AS PER INSTRUCTIONS, THE BAG CONTENTS WERE ALLOWED LEFT TO DRY AND THE NECESSARY REPORTS WERE COMPLETED. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF DAMAGE OR FAILURE ON THE CANVAS BAG. NO DAMAGE NOTICEABLE ON THE PLASTIC BOTTLE OTHER THAN THE LOOSE CAP. BAG WAS NOT LOADED IN THE ORIGINAL MIA-TGU FLIGHT. THE SPILL DID NOT AFFECT FLIGHT 795 NOR FLIGHT 953. PASSENGER WAS EADUCATED REGARDING THE CARRIAGE OF DANGEROUS GOODS BY AIR AND PROVIDED GUIDELINES ON FUTURE CARRIAGE OF THIS TYPE OF ARTICLES.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, DSR WILLIS NOTICED THE BOX WAS WET ON THE SIDE. THE PALLET WAS NOT BLOCKED, BRACED OR SECURED IN ANY WAY. FREIGHT WAS NOT SECURED, AND I SUSPECT THAT IT WAS SIMPLY BOUNCED AROUND UNTIL IT LEAKED. INGI TORFASON AND DAN FLEENOR OF THE QC DEPARTMENT WERE ON-HAND, AND PICTURES AND REPORT HAVE BEEN SENT OUT REGARDING THIS INCIDENT.

THE ENVIRONMENTAL CO-ORDINATOR INSPECTED THE BAG THAT WAS LEAKING AND FOUND A DARK LIQUID SUBSTANCE WITH A STRONG ALCOHOL/MOLASSES SMELL TO IT. AFTER OPENING THE BAG, A BROKEN ONE LITER BOTTLE OF AGED RUM WAS FOUND. THE ENVIRONMENTAL CO-ORDINATOR CHECKED THE REST OF THE BAG BUT DID NOT FIND ANYTHING ELSE AND, AT THAT POINT, CLOSED THE BAG AND PLACED IT IS A CLEAR PLASTIC BAG, ADVISING THE CREW WHAT HE BELIEVED TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. SOME TIME LATER A FLEET SERVICE CLERK CAME BY THE EC'S OFFICE AND QUESTIONED WHAT WAS FOUND. THE EC EXPLAINED THAT ONLY A BROKEN BOTTLE OF RUM AND SOME FOOD DAMAGED BY THE RUM HAD BEEN FOUND. THE CLERK LATER RETURNED AND ASKED THE EC TO CHECK IT AGAIN BECAUSE THE FIRST OFFICER WAS ALSO CONCERNED. THE EC AGREED RE-INSPECT THE BAG TO CLEAR ANY DOUBTS. BY THIS TIME THE BAG HAD BEEN TAKEN TO ANOTHER PART OF THE RAMP FOR THE AMERICAN EAGLE CONNECTING FLIGHT. THE BAG WAS LOCATED AND THE PASSENGER BROUGHT TO THE RAMP BY THE AMERICAN EAGLE CSM TO OPEN THE BAG. THE PASSENGER ADMITTED HE HAD SOME INSECTICIDE IN THE BAG THAT HE BOUGHT IN BARBADOS. THE PASSENDER SEARCHED FOR A SHIRT IN THE CENTER OF THE BAG, UNWRAPPED IT, AND FOUND THE BROKEN BOTTLE OF THE INSECTICIDE. THE BOTTLE WAS LABELED MALATHION 57%. AT THAT POINT THE SEO ON DUTY WAS CALLED AND PASSENGER INFORMATION WAS OBTAINED FOR  REPORTING PURPOSES.  THE BAGS AND THE CONTENTS FROM THE SPILL WERE HELD IN A 55-GALLON DRUM PENDING INSPECTION AND RELEASE BY THE FAA.  THE PASSENGER WAS ALLOWED TO LEAVE WITHOUT HIS LUGGAGE. THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL.

column168: FILE:3125-D, SHIPPER: VALSPAR, AWB# GVM 6957098621 LIT. ON 08/16/2002 AT 01:26 AN ODOR WAS CALLED IN AT BUILDING 207 AT DOOR H-2 IN A RED UNIT, LOAD DEVICE, LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS DONALD OSBORNE AND THOMAS CASPER RESPONDED. THE IMMEDIATE AREA WAS EVACUATED UNTIL RENDERED SAFE TO RETURN. UPON ARRIVAL THE TECHNICIANS DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN SEARCHING THROUGH THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE USING A PHOTO  IONIZING DETECTOR INSTRUMENT. THE DETECTOR ALARMED AS IT WAS PLACED NEAR THE ABOVE PACKAGE AND THERE WAS VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE TOP OF THE PACKAGE. THE TECHNICIANS REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE AND PLACED IT INTO TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD. THE TECHNICIANS TOOK THE PACKAGE TO A REPACK AREA OF BUILDING 207 AND BEGAN A MORE DETAILED VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE WA PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND DECLARED ACCORDING TO THE IATA REGULATIONS. UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE THE TECHNICIANS FOUND AN INNER 1 X 1 GALLON METAL RECEPTACLE INSIDE A SEALED PLASTIC BAG THAT APPEARED TO HAVE FAILED AS THERE WAS SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PLASTIC BAG. FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE INNER MOST METAL RECEPTACLE REVEALED THAT THE CLOSESURE  WAS SECURED BY A PLASTIC RING DESIGNED FOR THIS TYPE OF RECEPTACLE AS POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE IN PLACE. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE FAILURE WAS DUE TO THE INNER METAL RECEPTACLE BEING OVERFILLED. THE SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION 1H2 PLASTIC SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO ITS DESIGNATED DESTINATION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: TRAINMASTER PALICKI, AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S STANLEY YARD IN WALBRIDGE, OH, REPORTED THAT TANK CAR BIGX1019, LOAD ARGON, WAS DISCOVERED VENTING VAPORS FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THROUGH CHEMTREC.  MR. JOE CACCIOTTI, WITH AIR LIQUIDE ARRANGED TO HAVE A TECHNICIAN RESPONDED TO CHECK THE CAR.  ON 08-16, MR. CACCIOTTI REPORTED THAT THEIR TECHNICIAN INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE MAIN FILL VALVE ON THE CAR HAD VIBRATED OPEN SLIGHTLY, WAS LEAKING AND HAD ICED OVER.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED 1/8 TURN AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE TECHNICIAN OBSERVED THE CAR SOME TIME TO ENSURE THAT THE LEAK HAD STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DURING INSPECTION OF CSXT TRAIN Q341, FRA INSPECTOR L MATSINGER OBSERVED THAT THE MANWAY COVER ON TANK CAR UTLX 655139 WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED.  THE YARDMASTER OF LOCUST POINT YARD WAS INFORMED OF THE SITUATION AND HE IN TURN HAD THE TANK CAR SET OUT OF THE TRAIN IN A SAFE LOCATION.  THE SHIPPER OF THE TANK CAR WAS NOTIFIED AND INFORMED THAT THE CAR'S MANWAY WAS NOT SECURE.  THE SHIPPER SENT PERSONNEL TO THE YARD TO SECURE THE MANWAY LID. THE SHIPPER'S PERSONNEL FOUND THAT THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT.  THE MANWAY COVER AND BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS INSPECTED FOR OTHER SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  FINDING NO OTHER DEFECTS, THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: E.M.I JOB NUMBER: 17634 WHILE BEGINNING TO UNLOAD, THE DRIVER OF A CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS VEHICLE HEARD A HISSING SOUND AS IF GAS ESCAPING FROM ONE OR MORE OF THE CYLINDERS ON BOARD. HE PROMPTLY CLOSED THE TRAILER DOOR AND EXITED THE DOCK AREA. ONCE THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ONSITE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE VALVE ON ONE OF THE CYLINDERS WAS IN NEED OF BEING TIGHTENED. THE RESPONSE TEAM TIGHTENED THE LOOSE VALVE FITTING AND CHECKED FOR ANY LEAKAGE. THE LOSS SEEMED TO BE MINIMAL AS THE CYLINDERS APPEARED TO WEIGH THE SAME. THERE WAS NO PERSONNEL AFFECTED BY THE INCIDENT.

column168: E.M.I. JOB NUMBER:17632: DOE & INGALLS (D&I) PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THAT 2 DRUMS HAD FALLEN OVER FROM THE PALLET AND OBSERVED LIQUID MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. D&I PERSONNEL CONTACTED INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICES (IMS) AND REQUESTED A RESPONSE TEAM BEFORE THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED, D&I PERSONNEL HAD ALREADY OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM. CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAY, INC (Cf) WAS THE TRANSPORTER AND RESPONSIBLE PARTY. CF NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT OF THE INCIDENT. ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT CONTACTED IMS AND INFORMED THEM THAT CF WAS THEIR CLIENT AND REQUESTED THAT ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT MANAGE THE RESPONSE. IMS AGREED. A 1-FOOT BY 1-FOOT AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR HAD BEEN IMPACTED. APPROXIMATELY ONE  GALLON OF THE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE RESPONSE TEAM USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CLEAN UP THE IMPACTED AREA. THIS MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A 55-GALLON DRUM AND WOULD BE TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE IMS FACILITY PENDING DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS. D&I INFORMED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT THAT THE DRUM HAD A PUNCTURE HOLE ON THE BOTTOM. THERE WERE-NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: I ARRIVED AT KENDALL HEALTHCARE TO DELIVER A LOAD OF SULFURIC ACID.  UPON MY ARRIVAL I CHECKED IN WITH PLANT PERSONNEL TO VERIFY THE UNLOADING STATION AND TO PROVIDE A SAMPLE OF THE PRODUCT.  AFTER THE ANALYSIS OF THE SAMPLE WAS APPROVED, I THEN HAD MY SHIPPING PAPERS SIGNED VERIFYING THAT THE LOAD WAS CORRECT AND THAT THERE WAS SUFFICIENT ROOM IN THE CUSTOMER'S TANK TO ACCEPT THE LOAD.  AFTER PAPERWORK WAS COMPLETED, I THEN BEGAN TO HOOK UP MY UNLOADING LINE AND MAKE SURE THAT ALL CONNECTIONS HAD BEEN PROPERLY MADE AND THAT ALL SAFETY PRECAUTIONS HAD BEEN FOLLOWED ACCORDING TO COMPANY POLICY.  AFTER APPROXIMATELY TWENTY MINUTES INTO THE UNLOADING PROCESS, I NOTICED THAT SOME PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING FROM THE TOP OF THE CUSTOMER'S TANK.  I IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE VALVE ON MY TRAILER, STOPPING PRODUCT FLOW TO THE CUSTOMER'S TANK.  AFTER I TOOK A MOMENT TO VERIFY THAT THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED, I THEN WENT INSIDE TO NOTIFY PLANT PERSONNEL. AN EMPLOYEE IN THE RECEIVING AREA FOLLOWED ME OUTSIDE TO INSPECT THE INCIDENT.  HE ACKNOWLEDGED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE CONTAINMENT PIT.  HE SECURED HIS WATER HOSE AFTER I HAD RETURNED MY HOSES AND FITTING TO THE PROPER LOCATIONS ON MY VEHICLE.  HE ASKED ME IF MY PAPERWORK WAS SIGNED AND ACKNOWLEDGED MY DEPARTURE.  JOHNNY WALKER.

FREIGHT FREIGHT FELL IN TRANSIT DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING, CRUSHING CAUSING RELEASE.  ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS HANDLED ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  INSTRUCTION HAVE BEEN GIVEN AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TAKEN FOR ALL EMPLOYEES INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE.

column168: FILE: 3126-D, SHIPPER: MATTHEWS, AWB# DTP 6967176423 PHE.  ON 08/20/2002 AT 01:04 A CALL CAME IN OF AN ODOR OF INK COMING FROM A WHITE UNIT LOAD DEVICE AT DOOR H-4, BUILDING 207, LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS DONALD OSBORNE AND CAROLYN FRYE RESPONDED AFTER COMPLETING OTHER DUTIES IN THE OPERATION.  THE AREA WAS EVACUATED UNTIL IT WAS RENDERED SAFE TO RETURN.  UPON ARRIVAL AT 01:45, THE TECHNICIANS DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND USING A PHOTO IONIZING DETECTOR BEGAN SEARCHING THROUGH THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE TO IDENTIFY WHAT PACKAGE IS EMITTING THE ODOR.  THE DETECTORS ALARM SOUNDED WHEN IT WAS PLACED NEAR A PACKAGE THAT WAS MARKED AND LABELED, PRINTING INK UN 1210, FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THE PACKAGE WAS ONE OF TEN PACKAGES AND WAS MARKED AS BOX #4 OF 10 BOXES UNDER THE SAME AIR WAYBILL NUMBER AS IDENTIFIED ABOVE. THE TECHNICIANS DOUBLE BAGGED AND REMOVED THE 10 PIECE SHIPMENT OUT OF THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  THE TECHNICIANS OPENED THE PACKAGE MARKED #4 OF 10 AND FOUND 6 X 1/2 LITER EACH PLASTIC RECEPTACLES INSIDE OF A THICK PLASTIC BAG. THE TECHNICIANS OPENED THE BAG AND DISCOVERED 3 OF THE 6 PLASTIC RECEPTACLES HAD LEAKED AROUND THE CLOSURES, NONE OF WHICH WERE SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE ENTIRE 10 PIECE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO ITS DESIGNATED DESTINATION. CLEAR OF SCENE 02:00

ON 08/20/02 AT 03:38 A CALL CAME IN THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE THAT HAD AN ODOR OF PAINT AT DOOR B-7, BUILDING "B" OF OUR SORT HUB FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  THE AREA WAS EVACUATED UNTIL RENDERED SAFE TO RETURN.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS LORINE HARNER-JARRELL AND TERRY RUGGERIE RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL AT 03:44 THE TECHNICIANS DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND APPROACHED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION. THE TECHNICIANS NOTICED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT AND STAINED.  THE TECHNICIANS LOOKED FOR ANY MARKINGS, LABELS OR ATTACHMENTS THAT MIGHT INDICATE WHAT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED NO MARKINGS OR LABELS WERE FOUND ON THE OUTERMOST PACKAGING.  THE ONLY ATTACHMENT FOUND WAS THE AIRBORNE EXPRESS AIR WAYBILL, WHICH DID NOT DISCLOSE THE CONTENTS.  THE TECHNICIANS OPENED THE PACKAGE AND DISCOVERED A 1X1 GALLON METAL RECEPTACLE THAT WAS BADLY DENTED AND COMPROMISED.  THE TECHNICIANS DOUBLE BAGGED THE SHIPMENT ADDING AN ABSORBENT PAD AND REMOVED IT FROM THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN SENT TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT FACILITY WHERE IT WAS OVERPACKED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE DRUM AND PLACED IN THE SECURITY CAGE TO BE HELD FOR CONFIRMATION OF WHAT THE PRODUCT WAS.  THE ABOVE SHIPPER PROVIDED A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET THAT CONFIRMED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS IN FACT A REGULATED MATERIAL AND THEREFORE IT REMAINED IN THE SECURITY CAGE PENDING NOTIFICATION AND INVESTIGATION BY THE TSA.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 04:11.

column168: FILE: 2233-D, SHIPPER: GEMINI INDUSTRIES, INC., AWB# OKC 70833329372 DST. ON 08/20/02 AT 01:19 A CALL CAME IN OF AN ODOR OF AMMONIA AT DOOR A-18 IN A RED UNIT LOAD DEVICE IN BUILDING "A" OF OUR SORT HUB FACILITY LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, LORINE HARNER - JARRELL AND TERRY RUGERRIE RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION ARRIVING AT 01:28.  THE TECHNICIANS DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND OPENED THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE AND BEGAN TO SEARCH THROUGH IT OPENING PACKAGES TO DETERMINE WHICH PACKAGE MAY CONTAIN A PRODUCT THAT MAY POSSIBLY CONTAIN A PRODUCT THAT WOULD EMIT AN ODOR OF AMMONIA.  THE TECHNICIANS OPENED THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION AND FOUND INSIDE WADDED NEWSPAPER AND TWO ONE GALLON RECEPTACLES.  THE TECHNICIANS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE INNER ONE GALLON RECEPTACLES WAS A METAL RECTANGULAR CAN OF A COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID, NON-REGULATED AND THE OTHER WAS A ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUG TYPE RECEPTACLE THAT WAS MARKED MMO-370, AQUA AMMONIA.  THE CLOSURE WAS TAPED TO SECURE IT IN PLACE AND APPEARED TO HAVE FAILED ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY SIX OUNCES OF THE PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT.  THE NEWSPAPER WADDING ACTED AS AN ABSORBENT AND RETAINED THE LEAKING AMMONIA PRODUCT INSIDE THE PACKAGE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS DOUBLE BAGGED WITH AN ABSORBENT PAD AND SENT TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT FACILITY TO BE REPACKED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION STEEL DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN PLACED INTO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING NOTIFICATION AND TSA INVESTIGATION.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 02:00
PATRICK JOSEPH / IB FOS CAME IN FOR THE INBOUND SHIFT, WALKED THE DOCK AND FOUND THE BAG LAYING BY A DOCK DOOR.  HE IS INVESTIGATING WITH THE DSR WHO RETURNED THE PRODUCT ON WHAT HAPPENED....

column168: DSR KOBY WILLIS WAS UNLOADING CTRQ-027903 HE DID NOT NOTICE THE CARDBOARD COVERING THE DRUM AND PUNCTURED.  PRO# 206-001714 CAUSING 1.5 GALLON OF PRODUCT TO LEAK INSIDE TRAILER.  THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED, ALSO THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED.  DURING THIS TIME THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH DRY SWEEP AND CONTAINMENT BOOMS WERE PLACED AROUND THE TRAILER TO PREVENT PRODUCT FROM GOING INTO THE WATER SYSTEM.  ONCE PRODUCT INFORMATION AND CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES WERE ESTABLISHED THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC OVER-PACK DRUM.  THE REMAINING SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED AND PUT IN A DISPOSAL DRUM.  PRODUCT IS CURRENTLY SITTING IN SECURE LOCATION WAITING DISPOSITION.

column168: FILE:3127-D, SHIPPER: INLAND DIAMOND PRODUCTS, AWB# TRY 10406005470 MOS. ON 08/28/2002 ON 01:20 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 208 OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT BUILDING LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, DONALD OSBORNE AND CHRISTI COX RESPONDED ARRIVING AT 01:30.  THE AREA WAS EVACUATED UNTIL RENDERED SAFE TO RETURN.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS DONNED THEIR PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND BEGAN TO INSPECT THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION USING A PHOTO IONIZING DETECTOR TO DETERMINE IF THE PACKAGE WAS IN FACT EMITTING AN ODOR.  THE ALARM ON THE DETECTOR SOUNDED INDICATING THAT THE PACKAGE WAS EMITTING AN ODOR.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS DOUBLE BAGGED THE SHIPMENT AND REMOVED FROM THE AREA.  THE TECHNICIANS OPENED THE PACKAGE AND DISCOVERED THAT THE CLOSURE ON THE 1 X 4 LITER PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WAS LOOSE AND THAT THE ROOT CAUSE WAS DUE TO THE CLOSURE NOT BEING SECURE BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THERE WERE OTHER PRODUCTS IN THE PACKAGE, BUT WERE NON-HAZARDOUS/NON-REGULATED. THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A UN SPECIFICATION STEEL DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO ITS DESIGNATED DESTINATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: V-1 (OPERATOR JOHNSON) WAS DRIVING SOUTH BOUND ON US 167. V-1 WAS TRAVELING DOWN-GRADE AT A SPEED WHICH CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO OVERTURN WHILE NEGOTIATING A CURVE. TIREMARKS ON THE ROADWAY INDICATED THAT V-1 WAS TRAVELING TOO FAST TO NEGOTIATE THE CURVE WHICH CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO OVERTURN. V-1 OVERTURNED ONTO THE WEST SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. SLID ALONG THE SHOULDER AND COMPLETED ONE ROTATION. V-1 STRUCK A FENCE AND A TREE ALONG THE ROADSIDE. A WITNESS, UNKNOWN NAME, AND ANOTHER MOTORIST WERE FIRST AT THE SCENE. MR. ALBERT HURST,(501) 374-4177 WAS AT THE SCENE WHEN THIS OFFICER ARRIVED. THE UNKNOWN WITNESS HAD LEFT WITHOUT GIVING HER NAME. ACCORDING TO MR. HURST HE DID NOT SEE THE ACCIDENT OCCUR BUT THE UNKNOWN WITNESS TOLD HIM THE DRIVER WAS EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE. EVIDENCE OF INJURY TO THE DRIVER CONFIRMED THAT HE WAS EJECTED DURING THE ACCIDENT. V-1 WAS TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, SULFURIC ACID(PLACARD #1830). THE TANKER TRAILER WAS DAMAGED AND WAS LEAKING AROUND THE MIDSECTION AT OR NEAR A VALVE AT THE TOP OF THE TANK. THE TANK CAME TO REST ON THE LEFT SIDE AND WAS SPILLING THE CONTENTS. PETE REILLY, OFFICE EMERGENCY SERVICE, WAS AT SCENE AND DIRECTED ALL SAFETY AND CLEANUP EFFORTS.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURES, STABILIZED WITH ACIDS, WATER, AND NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT PEROXYACETIC ACID
column168: DRIVER BRAD IMSLAND WAS UNLOADING A DRUM OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE OFF OF THE TRAILER ONTO GREEN BAY PACKERS FACILITY USING HIS HAND CART WHEN HE HEARD A AIR TYPE SOUND COMING FROM DRUM WHEN LIFTED DRUM BY HANDLE ON TOP THE CHEMICAL HAD SPLASHED OUT OF OVERFLOW VALVE ONTO HANDLE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE THIS CAUSING HIS HAND TO GET CHEMICALS ON IT. HIS HAND THEN TURNED WHITE PLUS HE WAS GETTING TINGLING FEELINGS IN HIS FINGERS THE FIRST AIDE PERSON WASHED HANDS WITH WATER FOR 20 MINUTES.  DRIVER DID GO TO EMERGENCY ROOM AFTERWARDS BUT WAS TREATED AND OKAY. BASICALLY OVERFLOW AREA SPLASHED ON HANDLE CAUSING SPILL TO HAND.

V. CONSEQUENCES OF INCIDENT, DUE TO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL: #18 UNKNOWN - PENDING FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORT, MAXIMUM - 100 LBS OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, MAXIMUM - 67.32 LBS OXYGEN, COMPRESSED. VII. PACKAGING INFORMATION: #34 B&C - TWO SOURCES OF CYLINDERS ARE USED AND DUE TO FIRE DAMAGE IT IS UNKNOWN WHICH MANUFACTURER MADE THESE CYLINDERS. LUXFER CYLINDERS ARE MANUFACTURED TO DOT 4AL SPECIFICATIONS, CATALINA CYLINDERS MANUFACTURES THEIR CYLINDERS UNDER DOT-E7737.  #35 UNKNOWN DUE TO FIRE DAMAGE, #36 UNKNOWN DUE TO FIRE DAMAGE, #39 A&B UNKNOWN DUE TO FIRE DAMAGE, #40 B&C - TWO SOURCES OF CYLINDERS ARE USED AND DUE TO FIRE DAMAGE IT IS UNKNOWN WHICH MANUFACTURER MADE THESE CYLINDERS.  LUXFER CYLINDERS ARE MANUFACTURED TO DOT 4AL SPECIFICATIONS, CATALINA CYLINDERS MANUFACTURES THEIR CYLINDERS UNDER DOT-E7737.  IX. DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS: AT APPROXIMATELY 2145 HRS, 08/21/02, ALAN GRAHAM, AN APRIA EMPLOYEE, OBSERVED A FIRE BURNING INSIDE OF AN APRIA 2000 FORD E-350 VAN, VIN# 1FTSS34L9YHA82347 WHICH WAS PARKED IN THE DRIVEWAY AT HIS RESIDENCE, 6154 WHITESTONE ROAD, JACKSON, MS.  BEING A FIREMAN HE IMMEDIATELY GRABBED A GARDEN HOSE, APPROACHED THE SIDE DOOR TO THE CARGO COMPARTMENT, UNLOCKED AND OPENED THE DOOR.  HE INITIATED FIRE SUPPRESSION AGAINST THE FLAMES. MR. GRAHAM STATES THAT HIS DAUGHTER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE JACKSON FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HE CONTINUED TO ADDRESS THE FIRE.  AT FIRST HE THOUGHT THAT HE WOULD BE SUCCESSFUL IN EXTINGUISHING THE FLAMES, BUT THAT THERE WAS AN EXPLOSION AND HE STARTED TO RAPIDLY BACK AWAY FROM THE VEHICLE.  DURING THIS TIME HE RECEIVED MINOR BURNS.  SHORTLY AFTER THE INITIAL EXPLOSION THERE WERE MULTIPLE EXPLOSIONS AND THE VEHICLE BECAME FULLY ENGULFED IN FLAMES.  SHORTLY THEREAFTER, THE JACKSON FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE.  MR. GRAHAM WAS TREATED FOR MINOR BURNS AT ST. DOMINIC HOSPITAL AND RELEASED.  JEFFREY TAYLOR INVESTIGATED THE FIRE FOR THE JACKSON FIRE DEPARTMENT.  AS OF 09/11/02, PER VERNON HUGHES, TAYLOR'S SUPERVISOR, THE INVESTIGATION REPORT HAS NOT BEEN COMPLETED.  MR. HUGHES STATED THAT THE ORIGIN OF THE FIRE IS UNKNOWN AND THAT THEY WILL BE RULING IT AN "ACCIDENTAL FIRE OF UNKNOWN ORIGIN."  THE VEHICLE AND CONTENTS WERE DESTROYED.  THE VEHICLE CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN THE FORM OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, APPROXIMATELY 100 POUNDS AND OXYGEN, COMPRESSED, APPROXIMATELY 67.32 POUNDS AND MISCELLANEOUS OTHER ITEMS OF HOME HEALTHCARE, NON-HAZARDOUS PRODUCTS.  THE REMAINS OF ALL HAZMAT CONTAINERS WERE REPORTEDLY ACCOUNTED FOR BY FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL. ADDITIONAL INFORMATION WILL NOT BE AVAILABLE UNTIL THE JACKSON FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORT IS RELEASED.  THE RESIDENCES AT 6154 AND 6160 WHITESTONE ROAD RECEIVED DAMAGES FROM THE EXPLOSIONS IN AN AS YET UNDETERMINED AMOUNT.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE WET FIFTY POUND CARDBOARD CARTON CONTAINING ONE LEAKING FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED. APPROXIMATELY TWO POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE; THERE WAS A HOLE IN THE PAIL. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, AMPHOMAG, A BROOM AND A DUSTPAN. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND WET CARTON WERE PLACED INTO A FORTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LEAKING FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

DEBBIE, CORSICANA POLICE DEPARTMENT, REPORTED A RAILCAR NEAR THE 15TH STREET CROSSING IN CORSICANA, TX WAS EMITTING A STRONG ODOR. MICHAEL KELLY, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. DEBBIE ISSUED RMCC THE NUMBER AND NAME OF FIRE CHIEF MCMULLEN WHO WAS CURRENTLY ON SCENE. FIRE CHIEF MCMULLEN ADVISED THAT SEVERAL RESIDENTS IN THE AREA VOLUNTARILY LEFT THEIR HOMES BECAUSE THE ODOR WAS SO STRONG. MGR. KELLY REQUESTED THAT RMMCC NOTIFY CHEMTEC TO HAVE THE SHIPPER, AIR PRODUCTS AND CHEMICALS INCORPORATED, CONTACT HIM VIA CELL PHONE. MR. KELLY ALSO REQUESTED STATE NOTIFICATIONS BE MADE. AT 12:44 AM, MILLARD BONIN, AIR PRODUCTS AND CHEMICALS INCORPORATED, CONFERRED WITH MICHAEL KELLY, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT IF MR. KELLY COULDN'T FIX THE TANKCAR, IT WOULD BE MOVED TO A NONRESIDENTIAL AREA. MGR. KELLY DETERMINED THE TANKCAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID VALVE AT THE VALVE STEM PACKING NUT ON THE A END OF THE CAR. THE PACKING WAS TIGHTENED AND THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE REST OF THE TANKCAR WAS INSPECTED AND ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE.  THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSPORTATION AND THE FIRE CREW WAS RELEASED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: UPRR'S RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE A SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A LEAKING TANK CAR OF GASOLINE IN THE 18TH STREET YARD IN KANSAS CITY, KS. MR SEKAVEC CONTACTED LES MAKOVEC, MTO AND DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AND WAS STILL RELEASING PRODUCT. MR SEKAVEC HAD MR MAKOVEC CONTACT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AS A PRECAUTION. ON ARRIVAL, MR SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH FIRE DEPARTMENT OFFICERS AND DISCUSSED A PLAN OF ACTION. A DISTANT ASSESSMENT OF THE CAR WAS DONE AND IT WAS VERIFIED THE CAR WAS STILL LEAKING PRODUCT. A WALK AROUND OF THE SCENE WAS PERFORMED WITH A MULTI-GAS MONITOR AND NO FLAMMABLE ATMOSPHERE WAS DETECTED ON THE GROUND OTHER THAN RIGHT UNDER THE CAR FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL BUILT A SMALL DAM TO PREVENT ANY RUN OFF MATERIAL FROM ENTERING A STORM DRAIN. THEY ALSO APPLIED A FOAM/VAPOR SUPPRESSION MATERIAL TO THE CAR TO REDUCE PRODUCTION OF VAPORS. MR. SEKAVEC CLIMBED THE TANK CAR AND, AFTER OPENING THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER, DETERMINED THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM BELOW THE LIQUID VALVE. AFTER REMOVING THE VALVE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE EXISTING GASKET WAS DEFECTIVE AND A NEW GASKET WAS FASHIONED FROM VITON AND INSTALLED. THE VALVE WAS REINSTALLED AND SECURED. THE CAR WAS MONITORED UNTIL IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WERE NO OTHER LEAKS FROM ANY OPENINGS ON THE CAR. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

DANNY, YARD CLERK, ADVISED THAT HE HAD RECEIVED A REPORT OF CONTAINER UGMU 869596 LEAKING IN THE INTERMODAL YARD, STALL BLUE 792.  MANAGER COOPER WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO EAST YARD INTERMODAL FACILITY.  INSPECTION NOTED LEAKING RESIN AND APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD POOLED UNDER THE CONTAINER.  INSPECTION SHOWED THE LADING TO BE 55 GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED.  THE LAST ROW OF DRUMS AT THE DOOR WERE FLOOR LOADED, WITH THE LAST ROW OF TOP TIER DRUMS SEPARATED BY PLYWOOD SHEETING.  THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD WAS FOUR EACH 55 GALLON DRUMS ON PALLETS, DOUBLE STACKED TO THE NOSE WITH NO BILEVEL SEPARATION.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO REMOVE THE LADING TO INSPECT THE DRUMS.  ONE DRUM AT THE REAR WAS FOUND TO HAVE SPUN TO THE POINT THAT THE METAL UNDER THE TOP ROLLING HOOP WAS ALMOST WORN THROUGH, ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO WEEP.  TWO ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE DAMAGED BETWEEN THE TOP CHIME AND THE TOP ROLLING HOOP, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO WEEP.  ALL THREE DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  ESTIMATED A TOTAL OF FIVE GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST FROM THE LEAKING DRUMS.  ELEVEN ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE FOUND TO HAVE SUSTAINED DAMAGE THAT DEEMED THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSIT.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  ONCE THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER WAS CLEARED OF THE RESIDUE, THE LADING WAS PLACED BACK AND PREPARED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DAMAGED AND LEAKING DRUMS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR REQUEST.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: CHIEF CLERK, CITY OF INDUSTRY INTERMODAL FACILITY, REPORTED CONTAINER NOSU 455294, LOCATED ON ROW D, SPOT 693, WAS NOTED LEAKING.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. INSPECTION NOTED DRIED PRODUCT, CONSISTENT WITH THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE LISTED ON THE BILLING, AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE HAZ MAT CONTAINMENT AREA PENDING CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER.  THE LADING CONSISTED OF VARIOUS ZEP CLEANING PRODUCTS.  BLOCKING AND BRACING CONSISTED OF TY-GARD, WHICH WAS SUBSTANDARD TO PROPERLY RESTRAIN THE LADING. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO REMOVE AND INSPECT THE LADING. DURING THE OFF LOADING PROCESS, LOCATED A 275 GALLON TOTE THAT HAD THE TOP 6 INCH CLOSURE CAP LOOSE.  APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS HAD ESCAPED AND POOLED ON THE FLOORING OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CLOSURE WAS PROPERLY SECURED AND THE FLOORING CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE.  THE REMAINING HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES WERE LOCATED AND FOUND TO BE SECURE.  ALL OF THE LADING WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER AND PROPERLY SECURED FOR OVER THE ROAD DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.

ICTF SECURITY NOTED CONTAINER CLHU 284093 LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS, WHILE PARKED IN SPACE GREEN 52.  DEAN COOPER, TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  INSPECTION NOTED ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD POOLED ON THE PAVEMENT.  THE CONTAINER WAS 'DIAPERED' AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR INTERIOR INSPECTION.  UPON OPENING THE CONTAINER, NOTED THE LADING CONSISTED OF 80 EACH, DOUBLE STACKED 55 GALLON DRUMS. BLOCK AND BRACING CONSISTED OF 2X6 LUMBER IN THE BULL SLOTS.  PRODUCT WAS POOLING ON THE FLOORING AT THE REAR OF THE LADING.  DUE TO THE CONFIGURATION OF THE LOAD, IT WAS NOT POSSIBLE TO IDENTIFY THE EXACT SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO OFF LOAD THE CONTENTS AND INSPECT THE DRUMS.  WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, THE FOUR FLOOR LOADED DRUMS AT THE REAR WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME. THE REAR SILL/METAL DECK PLATE OF THE FLOORING WAS HIGHER THAN THAN THE WOOD FLOORING THROUGH OUT THE REMAINDER OF THE CONTAINER, CAUSING THE DRUMS TO SET ON AN UNEVEN SURFACE.  THE BOTTOM CHIMES RUBBED AND VIBRATED AGAINST THE METAL SILL DURING TRANSIT, WHICH EVENTUALLY WORE THE METAL TO THE POINT OF FAILURE.  TWO OF THE DRUMS LOST AN ESTIMATED 35 GALLONS OF PRODUCT EACH, THE OTHER TWO DRUMS ONLY LOST 5 GALLONS EACH.  THE DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  WHILE UNLOADING THE REMAINDER OF THE DRUMS IT WAS NOTED THAT CUT STRIPS OF PLYWOOD WERE USED FOR BILEVEL SEPARATION, AND SHEETS OF CARDBOARD HAD BEEN PLACED ON TOP OF THE PLYWOOD. THE CUT PIECES OF PLYWOOD ONLY ALLOW THE DRUMS TO SIT ON A PARTIAL SURFACE, WHERE AS A FULL SHEET OF PLYWOOD WILL SUPPORT THE FULL BOTTOM SURFACE TO THE DRUMS.  WITH THE ADDED CARDBOARD SHEETS, THE DRUM SPUN AND CUT INTO THE CARDBOARD, CREATING AND UNEVEN SURFACE FOR THE DRUMS TO REST UPON.  ONCE THE DRUMS SETTLED INTO THE CARDBOARD THEY BEGAN TO MOVE AND SHIFT SIDE TO SIDE, AFFECTING THE ADJACENT DRUMS, WHICH EVENTUALLY CAUSED THE ENTIRE LOAD TO BECOME LOOSE.  A TOTAL OF 54 DRUMS WERE FOUND WITH SUFFICIENT DAMAGE TO WARRANT THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSIT.  ONE ADDITIONAL WAS LOCATED LEAKING IN THE TOP TIER OF DRUMS AT THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER, WHICH HAD ABRASIONS FROM THE SIDE WALL OF THE CONTAINER AND ADJACENT DRUMS.  ESTIMATED LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS 15 GALLONS.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR SECUREMENT.  AFTER CONSULTING THE MANUFACTURER, IT WAS DECIDED TO PLACE ALL THE DAMAGED DRUMS INTO SALVAGE ORIGINAL CONTAINER, AND THE SECONDARY CONTAINER FOR THE RETURN TRIP.  P&O NEDLLOYD WILL INSPECT AND EVALUATE THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER CONDITION UP RETURN.

MR BIES SAID THAT WHEN HE LIFTED THE PALLET AND TAKE IT DOWN OFF THE LOAD RACK HE HEARD A LITTLE BUMP. WHEN HE RETURNED AFTER TAKING THE PALLET NEXT DOOR FOR XJV HE SAW THE CARTON LAYING ON THE LOAD RACK. HE BELIEVES THAT THE CARTON FELL OFF THE PALLET IT WAS LOADED ON AND THAT MADE THE DENT WHICH CAUSED THE LEAK, OR IT HAPPENED DURING O/B AT XCL AND THEY LOADED THE CARTON SO IT WOULDN'T BE DETECTED UNTIL UNLOADING.

column168: DRIVER BACKED BLEEDER (SPITTER) VALVE OUT MORE THAN 3 TURNS AND IT CAME OFF.  WHEN IT CAME OFF, THE SEAL BLEW OFF.  THE DRIVER PICKED UP THE CAP AND PUT IT BACK ON - WITH SEAL MISSING IT CONTINUED TO LEAK.. THERE WOULD BE NO WAY TO STOP THIS LEAK.  THE DRIVER DID THE CORRECT ACTION TO MINIMIZE EVERYONE'S EXPOSURE TO THIS INCIDENT.

DOUG LORD, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS - CEDAR RAPIDS, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 13312 VENTED WHEN MOVED.  THE TANKCAR WAS ISOLATED ON THE BEVERLY YARD, YARD 2 TRACK 20.  MR. LORD REPORTED THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE WAYBILL WAS CALLED AND RESCAR, ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR, RESPONDED.  LARRY WILDER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED.  RESCAR PERSONNEL DETERMINED THAT THE FRAGIBLE DISC IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE HAD RUPTURED.  THEY REPLACED THE RUPTURED DISC AND RELEASED THE CAR.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, EXPOSURES, OR EVACUATIONS.

THIS DRUM WAS PICKED UP FROM THE GENERATOR AT 1:00PM ON WED 8/21/02.  AT THE TIME OF THE PICK UP THERE WAS NO SIGN OF LEAKAGE OR DAMAGE TO THE DRUM RECOGNIZED BY THE HERITAGE DRIVER OR THE GENERATOR.  AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 PM ON THE RETURN TO HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL (TOLEDO DIVISION) ON I-75 NORTHBOUND ANOTHER DRIVER WHO WAS DRIVING DIRECTLY BEHIND THIS HERITAGE TRUCK INFORMED THE DRIVER THAT SOME MATERIAL HAD STARTED TO DRIP OUT OF THE BACK DOOR.  THE HERITAGE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND INSPECTED THE CARGO.  FINDING A DRUM WITH A VERY SMALL HOLE IN THE SIDE NEAR THE BOTTOM THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE TOLEDO OFFICE AND REPORTED THE LEAK.  AN EMERGENCY CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO OVER PACK THE LEAKING DRUM AND CLEAN UP RESIDUES.  AFTER CALLING TO THE CORPORATE OFFICE TO VERIFY A PLAN OF ACTION THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED AT 4:30PM AS WELL AS LOCAL EPA, AND THE LOCAL EMA.  STATE DOT WAS ON SITE THROUGH OUT THE CLEAN UP. STATE DOT REPORT NUMBER OH3210300200.  AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT THE TOLEDO OFFICE OF HERITAGE IS STEPPING UP TRAINING WITH ALL DRIVERS ON INSPECTING ALL CONTAINERS BEFORE TRANSPORTATION AS WELL AS COMPATIBILITY OF MATERIALS WITH CONTAINER TYPES TO BE CONDUCTED WITHIN 30 DAYS OF THIS INCIDENT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR APPLICATOR RIG WAS INVOLVED IN A ROLL OVER ACCIDENT.  THE RIG WAS ON ITS TOP AND THE LID OF THE TANK OPENED SPILLING 700 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID.  THE DIRT UNDER THE SPILL WAS DUG UP AND TAKEN TO OUR YARD.

column42: BUTYLENE SEE ALSO PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED
column168: OUR DRIVER GARY D. SMITH HAD DELIVERED A LOAD OF BUTYLENE (UN1012 AT EXXON IN BATON ROUGE AND WAS PROCEEDING TO OBTAIN ANOTHER LOAD.  MR. SMITH APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF HWY 75 & HWY 3115 AND MADE HIS STOP.  MR. SMITH OBSERVED A TRUCK APPROACHING BUT JUDGED THAT HE HAD TIME TO MAKE HIS TURN FROM THE STOP SIGN.  MR. SMITH MISJUDGED THE SPEED OF THE OTHER VEHICLE WHICH WAS A DUMP TRUCK LOADED WITH SAND.  THE OTHER VEHICLE STRUCK ABOUT MIDWAY OF OUR TRAILER, CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE PIPING.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF NITROGEN WAS RELEASED FROM THE PIPING.  NITROGEN  WAS USED TO PURGE THE PIPING ON THIS TANK AFTER THE UNLOADING PROCESS AT EXXON BATON ROUGE.  THE DRIVER OF THE DUMP TRUCK WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL BY AMBULANCE BUT WAS RELEASED AND LATER RETURNED TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE.  A SMALL QUANTITY OF ENGINE OIL AND DIESEL WAS SPILLED AT THE SCENE AND US ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO REMEDIATE THE SCENE AND PROPERLY DISPOSE OF THE RESULTING CONTAMINATED MATERIAL.  BOTH VEHICLES WERE TOWED FROM THE SCENE AND MR. SMITH WAS REQUIRED TO TAKE BOTH AN ALCOHOL AND DRUG SCREEN FOLLOWING THE ACCIDENT.
